1. Digital Input

Digital input pins are used to read two states: HIGH (1) or LOW (0). They are commonly used with switches, push buttons, and digital sensors.
Example: Push button connected to pin 7.
IoT Use Case: Smart doorbell system where a button press sends a notification.


2. Digital Output

Digital output pins are used to control devices by sending HIGH or LOW signals.
Example: LED connected to pin 13.
IoT Use Case: Turning ON/OFF a relay in a home automation system.



3. Analog Input
Analog input pins read continuously varying voltages using the ADC (Analog-to-Digital Converter). Arduino UNO has pins A0–A5.
Example: Potentiometer connected to pin A0.
IoT Use Case: Reading temperature, light intensity, or soil moisture sensors.



4. PWM Output

PWM (Pulse Width Modulation) pins generate a variable duty cycle signal to simulate analog output. On Arduino UNO, PWM pins are 3, 5, 6, 9, 10, and 11.
Example: Controlling LED brightness.
IoT Use Case: Motor speed control in smart robotics.



5. I²C Pins

I²C communication uses two pins:
SDA → A4
SCL → A5
It allows multiple devices to communicate using only two wires.
Example: OLED display.
IoT Use Case: Connecting environmental sensors in a weather monitoring system.




6. SPI Pins

SPI communication pins on Arduino UNO are:
MOSI → D11
MISO → D12
SCK → D13
SS → D10
SPI provides high-speed communication between devices.
Example: SD card module.
IoT Use Case: Data logging system storing sensor data on an SD card
